and we're gonna be out of a job.

12:40.180 --> 12:41.480
We just-- We need good players.
We need good players.

12:41.680 --> 12:44.020
Great. Good players.
Barkley, Stockton, Thorpe.

12:44.220 --> 12:45.400
I really like Stockton.

12:45.590 --> 12:48.060
Do you even know where Gonzaga is?

12:48.260 --> 12:50.060
I didn't say it's ideal, okay?
It's a name,

12:50.260 --> 12:51.560
which is better than
what you've given me, okay?

12:51.760 --> 12:53.370
- Rob. Rob.
- Yeah? What?

12:54.750 --> 12:56.150
What about Jordan?

12:56.340 --> 12:58.690
(scoffs) Sonny, we can't get
fucking Michael Jordan.

12:58.890 --> 13:01.310
Okay? I listened to Falk for three hours.

13:01.510 --> 13:02.400
He's too expensive.

13:02.590 --> 13:03.520
- Sorry.
- Mr. Strasser.

13:03.720 --> 13:05.350
Huh? Hello. Hi.

13:05.550 --> 13:07.150
- Richard.
- Yeah. Hi. Hi, Richard.

13:07.340 --> 13:08.810
I'd love to get some time
on your calendar.

13:09.010 --> 13:10.980
Okay. That sounds fun.
Can you let Doreen know?

13:11.180 --> 13:12.350
Roger that. Will do.

13:12.550 --> 13:13.980
- Roger, thank you.
- Richard.

13:14.180 --> 13:15.810
Yeah, yeah. Just rogering you back there.

13:16.010 --> 13:16.900
- Yeah.
- That's what that was, okay?

13:17.090 --> 13:18.350
- Thanks, Richard.
- Thank you.

13:18.550 --> 13:19.770
Bye.

13:19.970 --> 13:20.900
(sighs):
Oh, God.

13:21.090 --> 13:22.810
You know, there-- Thank you.

13:23.010 --> 13:24.730
There, uh, there used to be a time

13:24.930 --> 13:26.810
where I could name
everybody who worked here.

13:27.010 --> 13:28.900
Ah, things change.

13:29.090 --> 13:30.770
Places grow.

13:30.970 --> 13:32.100
That's true.

13:32.300 --> 13:33.770
Hey, you want some dessert?

13:33.970 --> 13:35.440
It's sundae bar day.

13:35.640 --> 13:36.810
Hi.

13:37.010 --> 13:38.400
Uh, I have a meeting.

13:38.590 --> 13:39.980
With who?

13:40.180 --> 13:42.060
The shoe dog.

13:42.260 --> 13:43.810
♪ Nasty dogs ♪

13:44.010 --> 13:47.950
♪ Atomic dog ♪

13:48.950 --> 13:52.850
♪ Atomic dog ♪

13:53.050 --> 13:54.310
♪ Yeah, life on all fours ♪

13:54.510 --> 13:55.650
♪ When you're out there on the street ♪

13:55.840 --> 13:57.230
♪ When they're out there
walking the streets ♪

13:57.430 --> 13:59.350
♪ May compete ♪

13:59.550 --> 14:01.730
- ♪ Nothing but the dog in ya ♪
- ♪ Oh, the dog in ya ♪

14:01.930 --> 14:03.060
♪ Bow-wow-wow, yippie-yo, yippie-yay ♪

14:03.260 --> 14:05.850
♪ Bow-wow, yippie-yo, yippie-yay ♪

14:06.050 --> 14:06.850
♪ Bow-wow-wow... ♪

14:07.050 --> 14:07.900
Hey, Sonny.

14:08.090 --> 14:09.400
Hey, Katrina.

14:09.590 --> 14:11.270
- (intercom beeps)
- Sonny's coming in.

14:11.470 --> 14:13.850
♪ When they're out there
walking the streets... ♪

14:14.050 --> 14:15.100
(song fades)

14:15.300 --> 14:16.520
KNIGHT:
Sonny.

14:16.720 --> 14:18.440
I'm missing the sundae bar, Phil.

14:18.640 --> 14:19.810
(door closes)

14:20.010 --> 14:22.480
Why do you think this guy is
skateboarding to work?

14:22.680 --> 14:24.940
We're a public company.
Does he not have a car?

14:25.140 --> 14:26.350
SONNY:
Probably just some kid.

14:26.550 --> 14:27.520
He looks like he's 50 years old.

14:27.720 --> 14:29.580
He's bald and he has a beard.

14:30.620 --> 14:32.150
SONNY:
Is that Pete?

14:32.340 --> 14:33.770
KNIGHT:
Why would Pete skateboard to work?

14:33.970 --> 14:36.690
Maybe he's having a midlife crisis.

14:36.890 --> 14:39.310
Oh. I hope he doesn't scratch my car.

14:39.510 --> 14:41.600
- (sighs)
- It takes 17 layers of paint

14:41.800 --> 14:44.100
to achieve that precise color of purple.

14:44.300 --> 14:45.940
They call it "grape,"
which sounds kind of pedestrian,

14:46.140 --> 14:48.190
but it's pretty.

14:48.390 --> 14:50.600
Anyway, how was the strategy meeting?

14:50.800 --> 14:51.870
Disaster.

14:53.330 --> 14:55.450
Uh, wonderful. What's the plan?

14:56.540 --> 14:59.150
Piss away our tiny allocation
on three mediocre players again.

14:59.340 --> 15:01.150
Sonny, we had an annual loss.

15:01.340 --> 15:03.230
I had to lay off a quarter
of the fucking company, okay?

15:03.430 --> 15:06.100
- I know, Phil.
- Do you? Do you know

15:06.300 --> 15:07.900
the whole basketball division's
on the chopping block?

15:08.090 --> 15:09.310
That the board wants me to fire everybody?

15:09.510 --> 15:10.980
And I can't guarantee you,
without some improvement,

15:11.180 --> 15:13.440
that's not gonna happen
at the next board meeting.

15:13.640 --> 15:15.190
W-We need to increase spending.

15:15.390 --> 15:16.650
(scoffs)

15:16.840 --> 15:20.310
I brought you in here to grow
the basketball business.

15:20.510 --> 15:22.020
It's-it's smaller now.

15:22.220 --> 15:23.350
Is Strasser's number right?

15:23.550 --> 15:24.810
- 250K?
- Yeah.

15:25.010 --> 15:26.480
- All right, what about 500?
- No.

15:26.680 --> 15:29.350
You're lucky to have 250K.
I had to fight for that.

15:29.550 --> 15:30.810
Your balance sheet's a debacle.

15:31.010 --> 15:33.980
Half the running shoes in the country
that were sold last year were Nikes.

15:34.180 --> 15:35.270
It's 900 million in revenue.

15:35.470 --> 15:38.230
You want to spend 250K on basketball?

15:38.430 --> 15:40.310
You know what they're telling the board?

15:40.510 --> 15:43.850
There are potentially a million customers
for basketball shoes in the United States,

15:44.050 --> 15:46.850
who would wear those shoes
only when they're playing basketball.

15:47.050 --> 15:49.650
They're wondering if any investment
is worth the potential upside.

15:49.840 --> 15:51.600
Well, if a board member said it.

15:51.800 --> 15:53.290
The board...

15:54.290 --> 15:56.060
Basketball is the future.

15:56.260 --> 15:57.900
The NBA finals are on tape delay.

15:58.090 --> 15:59.230
It's literally the past.

15:59.430 --> 16:01.560
People watch basketball.

16:01.760 --> 16:04.730
You know, we took four golds
at the Olympics.

16:04.930 --> 16:06.520
And nobody gives a fuck.

16:06.720 --> 16:08.150
We dominate
the running shoe market, Sonny.

16:08.340 --> 16:10.310
200 million running shoes,
'cause that's what people do.

16:10.510 --> 16:11.480
They run.

16:11.680 --> 16:13.150
And when they walk,
they wear running shoes.

16:13.340 --> 16:14.730
And when they go to the store,
they wear running shoes,

16:14.930 --> 16:16.480
and when they go to work,
they wear running shoes.

16:16.680 --> 16:18.250
That's what they do.

16:19.700 --> 16:21.560
People are starting to ask me
what you do here.

16:21.760 --> 16:23.480
You know what I do here.

16:23.680 --> 16:25.400
I-I know you, I know you go

16:25.590 --> 16:27.310
to a lot of high school
basketball tournaments.

16:27.510 --> 16:30.230
And, uh, usually with a layover in Vegas.

16:30.430 --> 16:32.060
And I-I'm told that

16:32.260 --> 16:36.100
you're a basketball guru or wizard or...
(stammers)

16:36.300 --> 16:37.980
It's hard to quantify that to a board.

16:38.180 --> 16:39.480
You know what I do here.

16:39.680 --> 16:41.480
You're losing, Sonny.

16:41.680 --> 16:44.190
You know, just because you lose,
it doesn't mean it wasn't a good bet.

16:44.390 --> 16:45.400
This perfect results bullshit...

16:45.590 --> 16:47.310
- It's not bullshit.
- It is bullshit.

16:47.510 --> 16:49.150
It's not bullshit.
Those are the central principles

16:49.340 --> 16:51.150
that built this into
a billion-dollar business.

16:51.340 --> 16:52.980
I can't win if you don't
give me a bankroll.

16:53.180 --> 16:54.520
You have to be accountable.

16:54.720 --> 16:55.850
You're accountable. We're all accountable.

16:56.050 --> 16:57.020
I'm accountable to the board.

16:57.220 --> 16:58.310
I told you not to go public.

16:58.510 --> 16:59.480
I told you this would happen.

16:59.680 --> 17:00.770
- You'd get tight, you'd change.
- I see.

17:00.970 --> 17:02.400
- This happens at every company.
- Uh, does it?

17:02.590 --> 17:03.810
- All the companies you've taken public?
- Yeah, every company,

17:04.010 --> 17:05.350
all they care about
is the P and L statement

17:05.550 --> 17:06.650
and-and keeping the board happy.

17:06.840 --> 17:08.730
Do you run?

17:08.930 --> 17:10.810
(sighs)

17:11.010 --> 17:13.650
Is this gonna lead to some
Buddhist aphorism I don't want to hear?

17:13.840 --> 17:14.810
Do you run?

17:15.010 --> 17:16.730
(sighs)

17:16.930 --> 17:19.290
- No, Phil, I don't.
- It's hard.

17:20.330 --> 17:21.980
It's suffering. It's difficult.

17:22.180 --> 17:25.150
The illusion is that
the finish line is the destination,

17:25.340 --> 17:27.870
but the act itself is the destination.

17:28.910 --> 17:30.850
I need $500,000.

17:31.050 --> 17:32.520
(knock on door)

17:32.720 --> 17:34.690
Mr. Knight, your 1:00 p.m.

17:34.890 --> 17:35.950
Yeah.

17:40.040 --> 17:41.620
(chuckles) Okay, Phil.

17:42.790 --> 17:46.230
When you find a wise critic
who will point out your faults,

17:46.430 --> 17:49.690
follow him as you would
a map to a hidden treasure.

17:49.890 --> 17:51.620
SONNY:
And there it is.

17:52.830 --> 17:54.850
(thunder rumbling)

17:55.050 --> 17:57.000
♪ ♪

18:17.080 --> 18:19.290
♪ ♪

18:43.700 --> 18:45.660
♪ ♪

18:58.200 --> 19:00.200
(sportscast playing quietly on TV)

19:06.450 --> 19:07.750
(register beeping)

19:18.040 --> 19:20.850
Ah, <i>Street & Smith</i>. Basketball fan.

19:21.050 --> 19:22.980
- You want to buy it?
- Oh, no, no.

19:23.180 --> 19:25.040
- I read that one already.
- Oh, okay.

19:26.080 --> 19:27.810
Okay.

19:28.010 --> 19:30.310
- SONNY: I'll buy this one, though.
- Okay.

19:30.510 --> 19:33.060
Hey, what do you think of
the, uh, Blazers' draft pick?

19:33.260 --> 19:35.060
- Bowie?
- Yeah.

19:35.260 --> 19:37.560
(scoffs) I mean, he's not Hakeem,

19:37.760 --> 19:39.730
but I like him.

19:39.930 --> 19:41.770
You're not mad about Jordan?

19:41.970 --> 19:44.100
A guard? (scoffs) Hell nah.

19:44.300 --> 19:46.400
I mean, he's averaging, what, 17 points,

19:46.590 --> 19:48.560
- which is like ten in the NBA.
- Yeah.

19:48.760 --> 19:50.100
Even the Bulls GM said that he wasn't

19:50.300 --> 19:52.100
- going to change the team.
- Yeah, he wasn't-- Yeah, I saw.

19:52.300 --> 19:53.650
He wasn't gonna dominate.
Yeah, I read that.

19:53.840 --> 19:55.900
CLERK:
I mean, if he hadn't hit that one shot

19:56.090 --> 19:58.100
to win the title game
in the college championship,

19:58.300 --> 20:01.200
he probably would've never went
that high in the draft.

20:02.250 --> 20:05.270
He's too small to be as good
in the NBA as he was in college.

20:05.470 --> 20:07.270
You seem like a true fan.

20:07.470 --> 20:09.940
(sighs) I don't know, man.

20:10.140 --> 20:11.350
I just love playing ball.

20:11.550 --> 20:12.980
- Here you go.
- Have a great night.

20:13.180 --> 20:15.850
- You, too.
- Hey, you know where, uh, Gonzaga is?

20:16.050 --> 20:17.000
Spokane, Washington.

20:18.250 --> 20:20.190
Stockton's too short, too.

20:20.390 --> 20:21.350
(laughs)

20:21.550 --> 20:23.410
- Have a good night.
- You, too, man.

20:33.950 --> 20:35.100
ROY FIRESTONE (over TV):
Michael Cooper,

20:35.300 --> 20:36.650
the Los Angeles Lakers forward,
is our guest.

20:36.840 --> 20:38.060
We're gonna come back
in just a few moments to talk about

20:38.260 --> 20:39.810
his artistry, how he flies through the air

20:40.010 --> 20:42.850
with the greatest of ease with our guest.

20:43.050 --> 20:45.440
(<i>SportsLook</i> theme playing)

20:45.640 --> 20:49.230
This is the racket I won Wimbledon with,
and you could've bought it.

20:49.430 --> 20:50.310
Really.

20:50.510 --> 20:54.060
You see, the Ashe Comp 2 Racquet I use
comes right off the production line.

20:54.260 --> 20:57.350
And I don't customize my racket
because the Ashe Comp 2 is

20:57.550 --> 20:59.730
just the way I want it just the way it is.

20:59.930 --> 21:00.940
And it should be.

21:01.140 --> 21:03.850
Ed and I have worked together since 1969,

21:04.050 --> 21:06.730
putting in all the special features
we thought important.

21:06.930 --> 21:09.230
So this particular Head racket
could have gone to you

21:09.430 --> 21:11.190
as easily as to me.

21:11.390 --> 21:12.440
We planned it that way.

21:12.640 --> 21:14.580
(<i>SportsLook</i> theme playing)

21:17.700 --> 21:19.560
(VCR rewinding)

21:19.760 --> 21:21.520
...Michael Cooper, among other Lakers,

21:21.720 --> 21:23.650
has his own summer camp for young kids,

21:23.840 --> 21:25.650
and, uh, if you're interested...

21:25.840 --> 21:27.700
♪ ♪

21:36.950 --> 21:38.410
(VCR rewinds)

21:43.500 --> 21:45.330
(VCR rewinds)

21:48.370 --> 21:49.750
(VCR rewinds)

22:02.410 --> 22:04.410
(phones ringing)

22:08.750 --> 22:09.940
- Yeah? Huh?
- I got it.

22:10.140 --> 22:11.540
No, no. I'm talking...

22:22.330 --> 22:24.690
STRASSER: Um, and, you know,
you-you tend to get growth

22:24.890 --> 22:26.350
- when you shrink the, uh...
- SONNY: I need you.

22:26.550 --> 22:27.730
Sonny, I-I'm gonna be done
in five minutes.

22:27.930 --> 22:30.100
- I need you done now.
- Um, w-- you guys are busy.

22:30.300 --> 22:31.850
- Richard, uh...
- It's fine.

22:32.050 --> 22:34.060
STRASSER: Richard, I'm sorry.
We're gonna follow up, okay?

22:34.260 --> 22:35.190
Thank you.

22:35.390 --> 22:37.560
You know, uh, Sonny, in business,

22:37.760 --> 22:39.190
there's a way in which
we conduct ourselves.

22:39.390 --> 22:41.230
- Like we...
- I found him.

22:41.430 --> 22:43.690
- Who's that, Jesus?
- Sit down.

22:43.890 --> 22:44.980
Okay.

22:45.180 --> 22:46.730
(chuckles) Lynwood Robinson.

22:46.930 --> 22:49.440
That name mean anything to you?

22:49.640 --> 22:51.270
- No.
- Great recruit.

22:51.470 --> 22:53.520
Everybody was after this kid.
North Carolina got him.

22:53.720 --> 22:55.600
He actually announced
his decision to go there

22:55.800 --> 22:57.520
the same day that Michael Jordan did.

22:57.720 --> 22:59.690
It was actually bigger news
in the <i>Charlotte Observer</i>,

22:59.890 --> 23:00.770
got a bigger headline.

23:00.970 --> 23:03.900
Within two years, Lynwood Robinson
transfers to Appalachian State.

23:04.090 --> 23:05.230
Nobody heard about him again.

23:05.430 --> 23:06.790
Now, watch.

23:08.370 --> 23:10.400
STRASSER:
This is the 1982 championship.

23:10.590 --> 23:11.810
The shot that Jordan makes.

23:12.010 --> 23:13.060
I've seen this. Everyone's seen this.

23:13.260 --> 23:15.060
No, we've been looking at it wrong. Watch.

23:15.260 --> 23:16.650
Here's James Worthy, okay?

23:16.840 --> 23:19.480
Number one in his draft class,
another guy we had no chance of signing.

23:19.680 --> 23:21.560
- Correct.
- Why isn't he getting the ball?

23:21.760 --> 23:22.650
They're down by one.

23:22.840 --> 23:25.150
There's under a half a minute to go.

23:25.340 --> 23:26.650
Why isn't the superstar getting the ball?

23:26.840 --> 23:29.730
Why is the ball going to
the 18-year-old skinny freshman

23:29.930 --> 23:30.980
from Wilmington, North Carolina?

23:31.180 --> 23:33.810
Eh, they probably drew up
the play for Worthy,

23:34.010 --> 23:35.980
and Jordan was an option
in case Worthy was covered.

23:36.180 --> 23:37.270
No, that's wrong.

23:37.470 --> 23:39.600
Worthy is a decoy.

23:39.800 --> 23:41.060
We've been looking at this wrong. Look.

23:41.260 --> 23:42.310
He knows he's not getting the ball.

23:42.510 --> 23:43.900
They're in a 1-3-1 zone.

23:44.090 --> 23:46.350
What's gonna happen the second
Worthy comes across the lane?

23:46.550 --> 23:49.440
That zone's gonna collapse on him,
leaving Michael Jordan open in the corner,

23:49.640 --> 23:52.020
and the ball's gonna go to him,
and he's gonna shoot it.

23:52.220 --> 23:54.020
Look, when he shoots it,
he shoots it right away.

23:54.220 --> 23:55.900
He knows he's getting the ball.

23:56.090 --> 23:58.480
The play is drawn up for Jordan.

23:58.680 --> 24:01.520
And now that you know that...

24:01.720 --> 24:03.080
watch Jordan.

24:05.950 --> 24:08.690
You feel like your plane is
on its final descent,

24:08.890 --> 24:10.580
or are you just circling?

24:11.620 --> 24:13.330
Look at him.

24:14.370 --> 24:16.900
Look at how relaxed he is.

24:17.090 --> 24:19.690
Look, he wants the ball.
He's calling for the ball.

24:19.890 --> 24:21.940
The whole world is watching him.

24:22.140 --> 24:23.730
He's 18 years old.

24:23.930 --> 24:28.150
He's three seconds away
from the biggest shot of his life.

24:28.340 --> 24:31.980
And the biggest shot of Dean Smith's life.

24:32.180 --> 24:33.100
Remember the knock on Dean Smith?

24:33.300 --> 24:34.480
He couldn't win the big one.

24:34.680 --> 24:36.440
He'd been there three times,
couldn't get it done.

24:36.640 --> 24:38.650
This is his fourth
and maybe his last time.

24:38.840 --> 24:40.400
Dean Smith didn't even start freshmen.

24:40.590 --> 24:43.020
Michael's only the third freshman
to start for the guy.

24:43.220 --> 24:44.560
And what does he do?

24:44.760 --> 24:48.190
He puts the ball in the hands
of an 18-year-old freshman.

24:48.390 --> 24:50.060
Why?

24:50.260 --> 24:53.230
Because Dean sees
the same thing that I see.

24:53.430 --> 24:56.850
The same thing that Lynwood Robinson saw.

24:57.050 --> 24:58.120
Greatness.

25:05.540 --> 25:09.190
I don't want to sign three players.

25:09.390 --> 25:11.480
I want to sign one.

25:11.680 --> 25:12.910
I want to sign him.

25:13.950 --> 25:17.400
We build a shoe line around just him.

25:17.590 --> 25:20.560
We tap into something deeper,
into the player's identity.

25:20.760 --> 25:21.940
Into that.

25:22.140 --> 25:23.560
What's that mean?

25:23.760 --> 25:24.900
That he doesn't wear the shoe.

25:25.090 --> 25:26.400
He is the shoe.

25:26.590 --> 25:27.900
The shoe is him.

25:28.090 --> 25:30.480
You want to anthropomorphize the shoe?

25:30.680 --> 25:31.940
Put little legs and arms on it?

25:32.140 --> 25:33.850
(sighs)

25:34.050 --> 25:35.730
Have you seen the Arthur Ashe commercial?

25:35.930 --> 25:37.770
(stammers) "This is the racket
that I won Wimbledon with,

25:37.970 --> 25:39.560
that you could've bought it."

25:39.760 --> 25:41.850
We do that but with a shoe.

25:42.050 --> 25:43.850
I'm gonna blow a quick 20
right here, okay?

25:44.050 --> 25:45.600
It's gonna cost too much money.

25:45.800 --> 25:47.270
No, not if we bet it all on one guy.

25:47.470 --> 25:48.350
Too risky. You want the whole budget?

25:48.550 --> 25:50.350
- The whole budget.
- Can't do that.

25:50.550 --> 25:52.150
We're gonna spread it across
three or four players.

25:52.340 --> 25:53.980
- I've said that.
- We have 250K.

25:54.180 --> 25:55.310
We can get him for 250K.

25:55.510 --> 25:57.810
Guess who else has 250K.

25:58.010 --> 25:59.690
Adidas has 250K, too, okay?

25:59.890 --> 26:04.060
So even if we were to offer him $250,000,
Adidas would be able to match it.

26:04.260 --> 26:06.600
Meanwhile, all our other prospects
have signed with other teams.

26:06.800 --> 26:09.350
Plus, Jordan has made it abundantly clear,

26:09.550 --> 26:12.480
painfully clear,
that he doesn't want to come here.

26:12.680 --> 26:14.980
So you would have to have
a pretty compelling pitch.

26:15.180 --> 26:16.020
Do you have that?

26:16.220 --> 26:19.200
Yeah, I can tell him the one thing
the other companies can't compete with.

26:20.500 --> 26:23.370
Our basketball division
is fucking terrible.

26:25.040 --> 26:26.400
I do not love it.

26:26.590 --> 26:28.230
You think Phil gonna go for that?

26:28.430 --> 26:29.940
But you like the idea, right?

26:30.140 --> 26:32.150
- The idea? Of Michael Jordan?
- Yeah.

26:32.340 --> 26:34.190
- What you gonna offer him?
- The whole budget.

26:34.390 --> 26:36.150
As in nobody else getting no money?

26:36.340 --> 26:38.400
Phil is gonna fire you.

26:38.590 --> 26:39.810
Well, I can handle Phil.

26:40.010 --> 26:42.440
The key to Phil is make him afraid.

26:42.640 --> 26:44.020
You gonna get us both damn fired.

26:44.220 --> 26:47.060
Phil got a hundred million dollars

26:47.260 --> 26:50.850
and a life supply of them damn pink,
nut-hugging jogging shorts.

26:51.050 --> 26:53.150
The hell is he afraid of?

26:53.340 --> 26:55.100
Let's say you get Phil.

26:55.300 --> 26:56.690
How the hell you gonna get Michael?

26:56.890 --> 26:58.230
Michael is an Adidas guy.

26:58.430 --> 27:00.440
He loves Adidas. That's all he wear.

27:00.640 --> 27:02.600
Them badass warm-up suits, shell toe.

27:02.800 --> 27:03.980
Michael don't want to come to Nike

27:04.180 --> 27:06.150
badder than that damn guy
sitting in the briar patch.

27:06.340 --> 27:08.690
Well, I'll deal with that
after I deal with Phil.

27:08.890 --> 27:09.730
Phil ain't gonna do it.

27:09.930 --> 27:11.770
But you like the idea, right?

27:11.970 --> 27:13.250
I'd like to sign Jordan.

27:14.290 --> 27:17.020
But what I don't know is
what his agent gonna ask for.

27:17.220 --> 27:19.750
("The Message (Re-Mastered)" playing)

27:23.450 --> 27:24.910
(line ringing)

27:34.540 --> 27:35.730
SONNY (over phone):
David.

27:35.930 --> 27:36.940
Sonny, Sonny, Sonny.

27:37.140 --> 27:39.350
Good morning, Falk.

27:39.550 --> 27:41.770
It's the afternoon
for those of us in the real world.

27:41.970 --> 27:43.940
What's new in the wilds of Oregon?

27:44.140 --> 27:46.270
I hear Nike's getting out
of the basketball business.

27:46.470 --> 27:47.810
Who told you that?

27:48.010 --> 27:49.150
FALK:
You know, I have clients in other sports.

27:49.340 --> 27:51.400
I just signed Boomer Esiason,
great-looking kid,

27:51.590 --> 27:53.350
and Boomer-- it's interesting,
because what Boomer does...

27:53.550 --> 27:54.770
David, David, David.

27:54.970 --> 27:55.850
I don't give a fuck.

27:56.050 --> 27:59.100
I'm calling about... Michael Jordan.

27:59.300 --> 28:02.060
I told Strasser months ago,
it's never gonna happen.

28:02.260 --> 28:04.190
- Well, you never talked to me.
- I'm doing you a favor.

28:04.390 --> 28:06.440
Michael's not even taking
a meeting with you.

28:06.640 --> 28:08.440
- What do you mean?
- A meeting?

28:08.640 --> 28:10.770
Group of two, maybe four,
five executives in a room.

28:10.970 --> 28:12.350
They hear a pitch from a company.

28:12.550 --> 28:13.560
It's common business practice.

28:13.760 --> 28:14.650
Michael's not gonna be doing that at Nike.

28:14.840 --> 28:16.150
Don't fuck with me, Falk. Come on.

28:16.340 --> 28:17.900
Okay, wh-what are the bids looking like?

28:18.090 --> 28:19.230
It's not about the money.

28:19.430 --> 28:20.810
When someone says
it's not about the money,

28:21.010 --> 28:22.230
I know for sure it's about the money.

28:22.430 --> 28:23.900
We decided to stretch the envelope.

28:24.090 --> 28:26.980
We want to hear what each company can do
to promote Michael.

28:27.180 --> 28:29.270
Okay, w-well, then we're thinking
along the same lines.

28:29.470 --> 28:30.770
That's why I want to have a meeting.

28:30.970 --> 28:33.310
Sonny, world-class players
don't wear third-rate shoes.

28:33.510 --> 28:34.940
Just get me in the room.

28:35.140 --> 28:38.270
Sonny, as a friend, it's a waste of time.

28:38.470 --> 28:41.100
Off the record: Even though
UNC was a Converse school,

28:41.300 --> 28:43.290
Michael wore Adidas during practice.

28:44.620 --> 28:46.480
Put on Converse
right before the game started.

28:46.680 --> 28:47.940
The second the final buzzer sounded,

28:48.140 --> 28:49.600
- Adidas back on.
- (fingers snap)

28:49.800 --> 28:50.940
- Bullshit.
- Ask Dean.

28:51.140 --> 28:52.350
You said it was off the record.

28:52.550 --> 28:54.060
I didn't say you had to tell him
where you heard it.

28:54.260 --> 28:55.520
Trust me, Converse knows it, too.

28:55.720 --> 28:58.100
I've already seen
Adidas's mock-up presentation.

28:58.300 --> 29:00.190
Three words: state of the art.

29:00.390 --> 29:01.440
That's four.

29:01.640 --> 29:03.940
You're a stalking horse, at best.

29:04.140 --> 29:07.230
And a slow, fat stalking horse,
so you're not even credible.

29:07.430 --> 29:09.350
You know he'll be miserable at Adidas.

29:09.550 --> 29:11.980
I mean, it's a shit show over there
since Adolf died.

29:12.180 --> 29:13.900
Adi, Sonny. He went by Adi.

29:14.090 --> 29:15.480
His name was Adolf.

29:15.680 --> 29:16.980
I mean, the guy's name
was literally Adolf.

29:17.180 --> 29:18.690
- He was a good man.
- He kept the name.

29:18.890 --> 29:20.690
It's Adi. Adi Dassler.

29:20.890 --> 29:22.230
Adi-Das. Adidas.

29:22.430 --> 29:23.730
- That's what it stands for.
- He was in the Hitler Youth.

29:23.930 --> 29:25.400
No, he wasn't. Don't say that.

29:25.590 --> 29:27.850
I saw a picture of him
personally wearing a swastika.

29:28.050 --> 29:28.900
The guy had the haircut.

29:29.090 --> 29:31.100
- We all have a past.
- Look, David,

29:31.300 --> 29:33.350
some of us have our past
and some of us were Nazis.

29:33.550 --> 29:34.350
There's a line.

29:34.550 --> 29:35.850
Well, he's dead.

29:36.050 --> 29:37.350
We're meeting with the whole family.

29:37.550 --> 29:38.770
When's the meeting?

29:38.970 --> 29:41.560
Uh, Jordans go to Boston, uh, on Thursday.

29:41.760 --> 29:42.770
That's Converse.

29:42.970 --> 29:45.150
And then Nuremberg for Adidas on Saturday,
and then we're gonna close.

29:45.340 --> 29:46.980
- Nuremberg?
- Would you cut the shit?

29:47.180 --> 29:48.900
It's close to-- it's near there.

29:49.090 --> 29:50.660
They want to close is the point.

29:52.160 --> 29:53.870
What are they offering?

29:54.910 --> 29:57.520
I don't see a world
where it's south of 250.

29:57.720 --> 29:59.150
No fucking way.

29:59.340 --> 30:00.730
- SONNY: Let me explain.
- No.

30:00.930 --> 30:03.560
Listen. Michael Jordan is the player
we've been waiting for.

30:03.760 --> 30:07.230
Yeah, but you said the same thing about
Artis Gilmore last year and Bobby Jones.

30:07.430 --> 30:09.690
All right, well, if perfection is
the goal, then I'm doomed, right?

30:09.890 --> 30:11.600
I-I mean, I'm not gonna hit every shot.

30:11.800 --> 30:13.900
How about one shot? A shot, ever.

30:14.090 --> 30:15.310
It's part of gambling, Phil.

30:15.510 --> 30:17.770
- You don't win every hand.
- This isn't a craps table.

30:17.970 --> 30:19.150
And we don't have
unlimited checks to write...

30:19.340 --> 30:20.350
I'm not asking for unlimited.

30:20.550 --> 30:21.940
I'm asking for what you already budgeted.

30:22.140 --> 30:23.400
- On one player.
- Yes.

30:23.590 --> 30:25.600
Don't confuse desperation
with vision, Sonny.

30:25.800 --> 30:28.350
(sighs) We're actually
gonna need more than that.

30:28.550 --> 30:31.690
For a rookie who's never
set foot on an NBA court?

30:31.890 --> 30:34.310
That's the literal definition
of rookie, yeah.

30:34.510 --> 30:36.440
Magic Johnson doesn't have his own shoe.

30:36.640 --> 30:38.120
Exactly.

30:39.750 --> 30:41.600
I can't justify that to the board,
so there's no point

30:41.800 --> 30:42.850
- in having this discussion.
- All right.

30:43.050 --> 30:44.940
Let me put it to you this way.

30:45.140 --> 30:47.690
I'm willing to bet my career
on Michael Jordan.

30:47.890 --> 30:49.690
Oh, come on, man.

30:49.890 --> 30:51.850
You asked me what I do here.
This is what I do.

30:52.050 --> 30:53.230
I find you players.

30:53.430 --> 30:55.020
And I fucking feel it this time.

30:55.220 --> 30:57.060
Yeah, okay, it's risky.

30:57.260 --> 30:58.350
When you were selling sneakers

30:58.550 --> 31:00.060
out of the back of your Plymouth,
that was risky.

31:00.260 --> 31:02.270
It took balls.
I mean, that's why we're all here.

31:02.470 --> 31:03.730
Don't change that now.

31:03.930 --> 31:05.690
Phil, I mean, if you look at him,

31:05.890 --> 31:08.150
if you really look at Jordan like I did,

31:08.340 --> 31:09.900
you're gonna see exactly what I see.

31:10.090 --> 31:11.400
Which is what?

31:11.590 --> 31:14.060
The most competitive guy I have ever seen.

31:14.260 --> 31:15.950
He is a fucking killer.

31:17.450 --> 31:19.020
Who's the competition?

31:19.220 --> 31:22.100
- Well...
- Eh, don't talk. (grunts)

31:22.300 --> 31:24.350
♪ My Adidas walk through concert doors ♪

31:24.550 --> 31:26.190
♪ And roam all over coliseum floors ♪

31:26.390 --> 31:29.400
♪ I stepped on stage at Live Aid ♪

31:29.590 --> 31:32.020
♪ All the people gave
and the poor got paid... ♪

31:32.220 --> 31:35.270
I know the last thing any of us
want to talk about today is business.

31:35.470 --> 31:38.190
I... I can't imagine the grief.

31:38.390 --> 31:41.310
Ah, as Adi would say,

31:41.510 --> 31:42.850
we must go on.

31:43.050 --> 31:44.600
He did say that.

31:44.800 --> 31:47.520
We have a great opportunity
for Adidas America.

31:47.720 --> 31:49.560
- ♪ Yo, what's up? ♪
- ♪ My Adidas. ♪

31:49.760 --> 31:52.020
- Very good.
- Good. Mm-hmm.

31:52.220 --> 31:54.980
("Rock the Casbah" by The Clash playing)

31:55.180 --> 31:56.950
JOE DEAN:
We already got the number one pick.

31:58.410 --> 32:00.410
Who's next on the hit list?

32:02.870 --> 32:03.850
Scoreboard.

32:04.050 --> 32:06.100
What the fuck, guys? We're doing this?

32:06.300 --> 32:08.770
I don't know.
I mean, can-can we even get a meeting?

32:08.970 --> 32:11.100
- Rob?
- Phil, you're signing off on this?

32:11.300 --> 32:12.770
No, it's a stupid fucking idea.

32:12.970 --> 32:14.060
I said, "Can we get a meeting?"

32:14.260 --> 32:15.940
I'll call Falk.

32:16.140 --> 32:18.190
FALK: Submit an offer,
and then we can talk meeting.

32:18.390 --> 32:19.560
SONNY (over phone):
I can't do that.

32:19.760 --> 32:21.560
Then I have no responsibility
to inform my client.

32:21.760 --> 32:22.770
(sighs)

32:22.970 --> 32:25.440
250,000 is what you can expect.

32:25.640 --> 32:27.560
I need it in writing.

32:27.760 --> 32:30.440
When the offer comes, it'll be in writing.

32:30.640 --> 32:31.900
I look forward to seeing it.

32:32.090 --> 32:33.600
I can't wait to waste six hours
flying out there.

32:33.800 --> 32:37.310
Why can't you get a base on the East Coast
like a normal company?

32:37.510 --> 32:39.350
They love it out here.

32:39.550 --> 32:40.900
I'm glad they're happy.

32:41.090 --> 32:42.770
Hey, how are the parents?

32:42.970 --> 32:43.850
Smart as hell.

32:44.050 --> 32:45.940
Don't pull any bullshit on them.
They don't want to be sold to.

32:46.140 --> 32:48.020
Yeah? Are they home now in Carolina?

32:48.220 --> 32:50.690
Don't call them, okay?
I'm not fucking kidding.

32:50.890 --> 32:52.690
That'd be inappropriate
and unprofessional.

32:52.890 --> 32:54.730
S-So is outright refusing a meeting.

32:54.930 --> 32:56.440
That's just business.

32:56.640 --> 32:58.600
Why does Michael want Adidas?

32:58.800 --> 33:01.100
Because he likes their tracksuits.

33:01.300 --> 33:03.850
(stammers) We'll get him
every tracksuit he's ever wanted.

33:04.050 --> 33:05.650
He's a kid.
He's not thinking about what he will have.

33:05.840 --> 33:07.150
He's thinking about
what he doesn't have right now.

33:07.340 --> 33:08.150
You know what else he wants?

33:08.340 --> 33:09.980
- (sighs) What?
- Car.

33:10.180 --> 33:11.940
Red Mercedes 380SL.

33:12.140 --> 33:14.980
But fortunately he's got
an extremely savvy advisor

33:15.180 --> 33:16.520
who thinks long-term.

33:16.720 --> 33:20.160
You know, it's really your humility,
David, that's so impressive.

33:21.540 --> 33:23.150
You know what I think?

33:23.340 --> 33:25.150
You don't have authorization
to make a written offer.

33:25.340 --> 33:27.650
Unless I see an offer in writing,

33:27.840 --> 33:30.040
I have no obligation to inform my client.

33:31.040 --> 33:32.560
- David, don't fucking hang...
- (dial tone droning)

33:32.760 --> 33:34.500
(sighs)

33:36.540 --> 33:38.080
(sighs heavily)

33:43.700 --> 33:46.150
("Legs" by ZZ Top playing)

33:46.340 --> 33:47.940
Stan, hey.

33:48.140 --> 33:49.650
Get me a ticket to L.A., plane ticket.

33:49.840 --> 33:51.330
Leave it at the gate.

33:52.370 --> 33:53.520
Oh, hey, Al.

33:53.720 --> 33:54.850
I'm not gonna make the meeting
tomorrow morning.

33:55.050 --> 33:56.480
I got to go to L.A.
to see George Raveling.

33:56.680 --> 33:57.900
Who?

33:58.090 --> 33:59.520
How'd you get a job
in the basketball division?

33:59.720 --> 34:02.060
George Raveling,
coach at the Olympics, Iowa,

34:02.260 --> 34:04.150
best man at my wedding. Jesus, Al.

34:04.340 --> 34:06.410
♪ She got legs ♪

34:07.450 --> 34:10.660
♪ She knows how to use them ♪

34:11.750 --> 34:14.810
♪ She never begs ♪

34:15.010 --> 34:17.650
♪ She knows how to choose them... ♪

34:17.840 --> 34:20.270
- RAVELING: It's-it's... it's ridiculous.
- (Sonny chuckles)

34:20.470 --> 34:22.020
I tried.

34:22.220 --> 34:23.850
I tried to put the word in for you guys

34:24.050 --> 34:25.100
during the Olympics. Just...

34:25.300 --> 34:26.600
I know. I appreciate it, man.

34:26.800 --> 34:28.270
Michael's not coming to Nike.

34:28.470 --> 34:31.230
He doesn't even want to meet. You know?

34:31.430 --> 34:33.060
Uh, and believe me,

34:33.260 --> 34:36.400
I-I told him multiple times.

34:36.590 --> 34:38.060
And-and we got along.

34:38.260 --> 34:40.100
He just doesn't like the shoe.

34:40.300 --> 34:41.850
He never even worn the shoes.

34:42.050 --> 34:47.600
He did say if somebody was to buy him
a red Mercedes 380SL,

34:47.800 --> 34:51.440
he would sign a shoe contract
for life with anybody.

34:51.640 --> 34:52.900
Except Nike.

34:53.090 --> 34:55.450
- (chuckles)
- (laughing)

34:57.290 --> 34:58.770
There's nothing cool about Nike.

34:58.970 --> 35:00.690
Even what it means, "Adidas":

35:00.890 --> 35:02.560
"All day I dream about sex."

35:02.760 --> 35:04.440
- "Puma": "Please use my ass."
- That's not what it means.

35:04.640 --> 35:06.440
"Nike" has no-no meaning.

35:06.640 --> 35:08.440
How are the parents?

35:08.640 --> 35:11.190
Solid. She runs shit.

35:11.390 --> 35:12.270
- Really?
- Mm-hmm.

35:12.470 --> 35:15.230
Well, so maybe I should talk to her.

35:15.430 --> 35:17.150
Hey.

35:17.340 --> 35:19.310
You bypass the agents
and talk directly to the family,

35:19.510 --> 35:20.480
you're gonna lose your job.

35:20.680 --> 35:22.350
I don't know what's wrong with me.

35:22.550 --> 35:23.980
I been doing this 20 years.

35:24.180 --> 35:25.850
I've never had a feeling like this.

35:26.050 --> 35:27.980
You know when you get a feeling.

35:28.180 --> 35:29.440
- You know?
- Yeah.

35:29.640 --> 35:30.560
Know what?

35:30.760 --> 35:32.350
Don't lose that.

35:32.550 --> 35:34.230
Even if I get fired?

35:34.430 --> 35:35.850
Summer 1963.

35:36.050 --> 35:38.100
A friend of my father's
asked me and his son

35:38.300 --> 35:40.690
to come down to a march in town.

35:40.890 --> 35:44.650
Now, mind you,
I have a full scholarship at Villanova.

35:44.840 --> 35:46.770
- Mm-hmm.
- Right?

35:46.970 --> 35:49.190
But I got this feeling.

35:49.390 --> 35:51.190
Don't know why.

35:51.390 --> 35:53.190
So I go.

35:53.390 --> 35:54.520
I get down there.

35:54.720 --> 35:56.900
One of the organizers see
two six-four Black kids,

35:57.090 --> 35:59.730
and they're like, "Oh, you guys
want to help with security?"

35:59.930 --> 36:00.810
(both laugh)

36:01.010 --> 36:02.730
So now we're the Fruits of Islam.

36:02.930 --> 36:04.310
They take us down there.

36:04.510 --> 36:07.600
They throw us up onstage,
right on the podium.

36:07.800 --> 36:08.940
There's cameras.

36:09.140 --> 36:10.770
One of the boosters has to be
a Klan member.

36:10.970 --> 36:11.910
(stammers) You know?

36:14.290 --> 36:16.730
But this voice kept telling me
I should stay.

36:16.930 --> 36:20.730
And I'm there five hours,
and I'm just sweating like... (groans)

36:20.930 --> 36:23.770
Then I saw the last speaker's speech.

36:23.970 --> 36:26.900
We walked offstage.

36:27.090 --> 36:28.190
I said to him, I said,

36:28.390 --> 36:32.020
"Hey, that was the best speech
I ever heard."

36:32.220 --> 36:34.060
He said, "Thank you, young man."

36:34.260 --> 36:37.350
He takes the speech, he folds it up,
and he puts it in my pocket.

36:37.550 --> 36:39.560
Later, I'm looking for my favorite line.

36:39.760 --> 36:40.850
It's not in there.

36:41.050 --> 36:44.150
Then I notice the whole
second half of the speech

36:44.340 --> 36:45.580
is completely different.

36:47.450 --> 36:49.690
What was the line you were looking for?

36:49.890 --> 36:51.400
"I have a dream."

36:51.590 --> 36:53.310
Come on. Get the fuck out of here.

36:53.510 --> 36:55.270
- The "I Have a Dr--" You have that?
- Yeah.

36:55.470 --> 36:57.560
See, the first half,

36:57.760 --> 36:59.910
he noticed the audience wasn't with him.

37:00.950 --> 37:02.600
And he changed the whole thing,

37:02.800 --> 37:04.400
- made the whole speech up
- (fingers snap)

37:04.590 --> 37:06.900
- right there on the spot.
- Wow.

37:07.090 --> 37:09.900
So, are you saying I should contact
the Jordans and-and...

37:10.090 --> 37:11.770
Fuck no! (laughing)

37:11.970 --> 37:13.480
(laughing):
You just fucking said

37:13.680 --> 37:15.270
- that that's what I should do.
- No, but that's your voice.

37:15.470 --> 37:17.440
Your voice tells you to do stupid shit.

37:17.640 --> 37:20.850
- My voice made me a part of history.
- Yeah.

37:21.050 --> 37:22.480
(both laugh)

37:22.680 --> 37:23.770
You have the speech.

37:23.970 --> 37:25.540
That's incredible.

37:27.000 --> 37:28.310
I also have Abe Lincoln's.

37:28.510 --> 37:29.520
(both laughing)

37:29.720 --> 37:32.310
Were you doing security for that one, too?

37:32.510 --> 37:34.770
Oh, I'm fucking that old now?

37:34.970 --> 37:38.270
♪ What's your price for flight? ♪

37:38.470 --> 37:39.900
("Sister Christian" by Night Ranger
playing)

37:40.090 --> 37:44.160
♪ In finding Mr. Right ♪

37:45.580 --> 37:49.200
♪ You'll be all right tonight ♪

37:54.370 --> 37:58.810
♪ Babe, you know
you're growing up so fast... ♪

37:59.010 --> 38:00.020
(song fades)

38:00.220 --> 38:01.730
- Sonny.
- Hey.

38:01.930 --> 38:03.770
(sighs) Looking all over for you.

38:03.970 --> 38:05.100
I was just here, man,

38:05.300 --> 38:07.660
having a cup of coffee
before I got to the house.

38:08.660 --> 38:11.100
I'm thinking of reaching out
to the parents.

38:11.300 --> 38:13.500
- Reaching out to Jordan's parents?
- Yeah.

38:14.540 --> 38:16.690
Sonny, that ain't something
you take lightly, man.

38:16.890 --> 38:19.410
You go around Falk, you better close.

38:23.790 --> 38:25.200
Listen.

38:26.910 --> 38:27.940
You made me believe, man.

38:28.140 --> 38:30.400
Y-You started the Dapper Dan tournament.

38:30.590 --> 38:31.850
You got them all there,

38:32.050 --> 38:34.940
the greatest high school players
in the country.

38:35.140 --> 38:37.730
You might have forgot about this,
but I was invited.

38:37.930 --> 38:39.900
Best day of my life.

38:40.090 --> 38:41.830
Then I blew out my damn knee.

38:43.330 --> 38:44.700
