on this hand, sir?

52:47.220 --> 52:49.790
Maybe the deed to your house?

52:50.950 --> 52:53.850
SONNY: You're gonna need to pack
some pajamas for tomorrow.

52:54.050 --> 52:56.410
Um, we're not leaving the office.

52:57.830 --> 53:00.830
Michael Jordan is coming to Beaverton.

53:01.870 --> 53:03.540
Holy shit.

53:04.580 --> 53:06.290
Time to see Pete.

53:07.870 --> 53:10.200
("Let It Whip" by The Dazz Band playing)

53:19.120 --> 53:20.370
(elevator bell dings)

53:22.200 --> 53:24.310
♪ Wanna see you with it ♪

53:24.510 --> 53:26.150
♪ Sure could treat you right ♪

53:26.340 --> 53:29.560
♪ Give me just a minute
of your time tonight... ♪

53:29.760 --> 53:31.560
To what do I owe the honor?

53:31.760 --> 53:33.730
I need a shoe, Pete.

53:33.930 --> 53:35.650
I would assume as much.

53:35.840 --> 53:38.100
I need the greatest basketball shoe
that's ever been made.

53:38.300 --> 53:39.350
How long do we have?

53:39.550 --> 53:40.770
Monday.

53:40.970 --> 53:42.910
Step into my office.

53:44.500 --> 53:46.350
SONNY:
Hey, was that you, uh, on a skateboard

53:46.550 --> 53:48.060
- in the parking lot?
- Yes.

53:48.260 --> 53:49.270
What's that all about?

53:49.470 --> 53:51.190
I'm having a midlife crisis.

53:51.390 --> 53:52.810
- ♪ So let it whip ♪
- ♪ Let's whip it, baby ♪

53:53.010 --> 53:55.310
- ♪ Child ♪
- ♪ Let's whip it right... ♪

53:55.510 --> 53:57.020
SONNY:
It has to be individual.

53:57.220 --> 53:58.730
Like, think of it like this.

53:58.930 --> 54:01.150
Uh, Converse are plain,
ordinary shoes, right?

54:01.340 --> 54:03.060
Every player wears the same one.

54:03.260 --> 54:04.440
What we do with this one is,

54:04.640 --> 54:06.810
rather than have the athlete
wear one of our shoes,

54:07.010 --> 54:10.020
we create the shoe around the athlete.

54:10.220 --> 54:15.150
So the shoe is
a physical manifestation of the individual

54:15.340 --> 54:20.330
rather than the individual
as emblem of the corporate entity?

54:21.620 --> 54:22.690
Something like that.

54:22.890 --> 54:25.650
The requirements are:

54:25.840 --> 54:28.770
speak as an individual,

54:28.970 --> 54:31.850
market to a mass audience

54:32.050 --> 54:35.730
and be the most beautiful shoe
known to mankind.

54:35.930 --> 54:37.400
Yes.

54:37.590 --> 54:39.480
Form or function?

54:39.680 --> 54:41.540
Uh...

54:42.580 --> 54:46.270
Uh, something can be beautiful
or it can be practical.

54:46.470 --> 54:47.410
Rarely both.

54:48.450 --> 54:50.750
Come up with something new.

54:52.620 --> 54:56.400
Humans have been wearing shoes
for thousands of years,

54:56.590 --> 55:01.230
and the design has
substantively changed once:

55:01.430 --> 55:05.950
when they differentiated between
the right and the left shoe.

55:07.500 --> 55:09.660
That was 600 years ago.

55:10.700 --> 55:12.020
Let's go form.

55:12.220 --> 55:13.480
Beauty.

55:13.680 --> 55:14.560
Not function?

55:14.760 --> 55:16.730
You know what they say.

55:16.930 --> 55:19.020
Poetry only makes the world bearable.

55:19.220 --> 55:21.310
- It's engineering that got us to the moon.
- (pager beeping)

55:21.510 --> 55:23.310
Shit, I got to go.

55:23.510 --> 55:25.350
Hey, just get started today.

55:25.550 --> 55:28.060
Tomorrow's Saturday.

55:28.260 --> 55:31.190
Yeah, if you don't come in Saturday,
don't bother coming in Sunday.

55:31.390 --> 55:33.020
We're of like minds.

55:33.220 --> 55:35.370
Who's the player for the shoe?

55:36.830 --> 55:38.310
Michael Jordan.

55:38.510 --> 55:40.190
("All I Need Is a Miracle"
by Mike + The Mechanics playing)

55:40.390 --> 55:43.060
♪ All I need is a miracle ♪

55:43.260 --> 55:46.620
♪ All I need is you ♪

55:47.870 --> 55:50.190
♪ All I need is a miracle ♪

55:50.390 --> 55:52.480
♪ All I need is you... ♪

55:52.680 --> 55:54.770
Mrs. Jordan. It is a pleasure to meet you.

55:54.970 --> 55:57.150
- It's a pleasure meeting you.
- Mr. Jordan.

55:57.340 --> 55:59.480
We sure do appreciate you
making the long trip out here.

55:59.680 --> 56:02.100
- How are you? -Right this way.
- Good to see you. -Thank you.

56:02.300 --> 56:03.190
- Here we are.
- How was everything?

56:03.390 --> 56:05.350
- It was wonderful.
- Yes?

56:05.550 --> 56:06.900
ANNOUNCER:
<i>Converse All Stars.</i>

56:07.090 --> 56:11.230
They started out on the basketball court,
but now...

56:11.430 --> 56:13.150
They're everywhere.

56:13.340 --> 56:15.400
(electronic dance music playing)

56:15.590 --> 56:18.040
They're everywhere.

56:19.950 --> 56:20.980
They're everywhere.

56:21.180 --> 56:22.520
ANNOUNCER:
Converse All Stars.

56:22.720 --> 56:25.700
Official athletic shoe
of the 1984 Olympic Games.

56:30.040 --> 56:33.520
The feeling I get when I see Michael play,

56:33.720 --> 56:37.150
there are only a few other players
that gave me that feeling.

56:37.340 --> 56:40.150
And those players are here at Converse.

56:40.340 --> 56:41.520
(chuckles):
It is that simple.

56:41.720 --> 56:44.400
Michael, we're gonna treat you
like our superstars

56:44.590 --> 56:46.900
before you even set foot on an NBA court.

56:47.090 --> 56:48.480
FALK:
We're looking for a shoe

56:48.680 --> 56:51.150
that holds appeal
beyond the basketball court.

56:51.340 --> 56:53.480
Well, what could hold more appeal
than the shoe worn by

56:53.680 --> 56:55.480
the best players in the game?

56:55.680 --> 57:00.190
Tradition and history
are paramount at Converse.

57:00.390 --> 57:02.480
You have an impressive roster.

57:02.680 --> 57:04.810
Best three players in the league
in Magic Johnson,

57:05.010 --> 57:06.900
Larry Bird, Julius Erving.

57:07.090 --> 57:09.690
But another way of looking at this is

57:09.890 --> 57:13.270
that the best Michael will ever be
with you is number four.

57:13.470 --> 57:15.980
Frankly, ma'am, we're...

57:16.180 --> 57:19.540
we're talking about Magic Johnson
and Larry Bird here.

57:20.580 --> 57:22.600
H-He's gonna play like them.

57:22.800 --> 57:26.100
He's gonna be mentioned
in the same sentence with them.

57:26.300 --> 57:28.560
- What can be better than that?
- (chuckles)

57:28.760 --> 57:30.700
♪ ♪

57:31.910 --> 57:34.350
- (printer whirring)
- SONNY: No, they're too bland.

57:34.550 --> 57:36.560
They're j-just too white.
Not enough color in there.

57:36.760 --> 57:38.770
I mean, the Bulls are red and black.

57:38.970 --> 57:40.060
Can you get more red in?

57:40.260 --> 57:42.060
They literally are not permitted to be

57:42.260 --> 57:45.940
a single additional
percentage point of red.

57:46.140 --> 57:47.690
Is that true? What is the actual rule?

57:47.890 --> 57:50.350
51% of the shoe has to be white.

57:50.550 --> 57:52.150
NBA is extremely strict about it.

57:52.340 --> 57:53.940
They'll fine him.

57:54.140 --> 57:56.900
- They'll fine him?
- $5,000 a game.

57:57.090 --> 57:59.100
(sighs)

57:59.300 --> 58:00.830
We're fucked.

58:05.910 --> 58:07.950
What about more red?

58:10.250 --> 58:11.870
A lot more red.

58:13.450 --> 58:16.440
And what about if we just pay the fines?

58:16.640 --> 58:18.060
Make a commercial out of it.

58:18.260 --> 58:19.940
You know, it'll give us headlines.

58:20.140 --> 58:23.440
They're gonna fine Michael Jordan
for being too colorful.

58:23.640 --> 58:25.410
Yes.

58:27.200 --> 58:28.350
More red.

58:28.550 --> 58:30.560
That's right.

58:30.760 --> 58:32.950
Subversive. Individualistic.

58:34.580 --> 58:36.250
That's it.

58:38.620 --> 58:42.410
Do you men think about
basketball shoes often?

58:43.830 --> 58:45.770
- I mostly think about basketball.
- More marketing.

58:45.970 --> 58:46.910
Yeah.

58:49.330 --> 58:52.810
Basketball shoes are the...

58:53.010 --> 58:55.750
central preoccupation of my life.

58:56.790 --> 58:58.230
We know.

58:58.430 --> 59:02.730
I've had one persistent obsession

59:02.930 --> 59:05.770
that I've harbored and nurtured

59:05.970 --> 59:09.020
in hopes of making
the perfect basketball shoe.

59:09.220 --> 59:11.650
I've been trying to apply that

59:11.840 --> 59:14.440
to the Sole line.

59:14.640 --> 59:16.560
I thought it should be called...

59:16.760 --> 59:18.850
Air Sole, but...

59:19.050 --> 59:21.200
(sighs) That's not it.

59:23.000 --> 59:24.080
This is it.

59:25.500 --> 59:26.700
What is it?

59:27.750 --> 59:29.870
Air Jordan.

59:33.660 --> 59:34.870
That's perfect.

59:36.410 --> 59:37.730
Yeah.

59:37.930 --> 59:39.560
What's wrong?

59:39.760 --> 59:42.870
(sighs) I think David Falk
said the same name.

59:43.910 --> 59:45.000
STRASSER:
What?

59:47.540 --> 59:49.730
- You know, fuck that guy.
- Well, we just tell them he said it.

59:49.930 --> 59:50.810
- Yeah.
- You said it.

59:51.010 --> 59:52.270
- Okay, okay.
- David Falk him.

59:52.470 --> 59:53.690
- SONNY: Your idea, Pete.
- My-my idea.

59:53.890 --> 59:55.060
Yeah, Air Jordan.

59:55.260 --> 59:56.520
(typewriter dings)

59:56.720 --> 59:58.600
("Can't Fight This Feeling"
by REO Speedwagon playing)

59:58.800 --> 01:00:04.560
♪ And I can't fight this feeling anymore ♪

01:00:04.760 --> 01:00:10.770
♪ I've forgotten
what I started fighting for ♪

01:00:10.970 --> 01:00:15.150
♪ It's time to bring this ship
into the shore ♪

01:00:15.340 --> 01:00:18.020
♪ And throw away the oars ♪

01:00:18.220 --> 01:00:20.440
- ♪ Forever... ♪
- (song fades)

01:00:20.640 --> 01:00:22.190
SONNY:
I like this place better when it's empty.

01:00:22.390 --> 01:00:23.600
What does that say about me?

01:00:23.800 --> 01:00:28.150
You know, Sonny, this doesn't work out,
jobs are gone, checks are gone.

01:00:28.340 --> 01:00:29.560
You know that, right?

01:00:29.760 --> 01:00:31.150
Well, you'll get another job.

01:00:31.340 --> 01:00:33.190
What I do you can't put on a résumé.

01:00:33.390 --> 01:00:36.270
I wouldn't worry about it.
You're very, very convincing.

01:00:36.470 --> 01:00:38.100
Yeah. That's my job.

01:00:38.300 --> 01:00:41.400
But I also know that sometimes people
can be completely and totally wrong.

01:00:41.590 --> 01:00:42.900
- (laughs)
- Okay?

01:00:43.090 --> 01:00:45.270
You know, like-like somebody
really sold the emperor on,

01:00:45.470 --> 01:00:47.400
"We should bomb Pearl Harbor," okay?

01:00:47.590 --> 01:00:49.230
Are you likening yourself to Hirohito?

01:00:49.430 --> 01:00:51.560
We can take this stuff, right?
'Cause the cashier's not here.

01:00:51.760 --> 01:00:53.100
Well, I mean, in a way, I am.

01:00:53.300 --> 01:00:55.520
You know, uh, you know that-that new, uh,

01:00:55.720 --> 01:00:58.600
Springsteen song, "Born in the U.S.A."?

01:00:58.800 --> 01:01:00.900
- Yeah, everybody knows that song, Rob.
- Huh? Yeah.

01:01:01.090 --> 01:01:04.020
So I, so I got that
in the tape deck in the car.

01:01:04.220 --> 01:01:06.690
Listen to it every morning,
get all psyched up.

01:01:06.890 --> 01:01:08.850
You know, I just-- I really sing it.

01:01:09.050 --> 01:01:14.100
I'm, you know, fired up about
American freedom and...

01:01:14.300 --> 01:01:15.480
Uh, I can imagine.

01:01:15.680 --> 01:01:18.650
Uh, but th-this morning,
I really focused on the words,

01:01:18.840 --> 01:01:20.940
and it is not about freedom.

01:01:21.140 --> 01:01:23.480
Like, not in any way.

01:01:23.680 --> 01:01:26.020
It's about a guy who comes home
from Vietnam, can't find a job,

01:01:26.220 --> 01:01:29.310
and I'm just belting it out
enthusiastically.

01:01:29.510 --> 01:01:33.440
Just completely wrong idea.

01:01:33.640 --> 01:01:36.230
And, you know, uh, we actually make, uh,

01:01:36.430 --> 01:01:40.440
about 80% of our shoes
in South Korea, Taiwan.

01:01:40.640 --> 01:01:44.020
Um, and I know I should be
ambivalent about that,

01:01:44.220 --> 01:01:45.350
but-but I'm-I'm not.

01:01:45.550 --> 01:01:47.690
Um... (smacks lips)

01:01:47.890 --> 01:01:52.410
The judge in the divorce, uh,
she just gave me Sundays.

01:01:53.450 --> 01:01:56.730
Yeah, you get to be a-a dad
for four hours every Sunday at the park.

01:01:56.930 --> 01:01:59.690
That's the only time I see Avery.

01:01:59.890 --> 01:02:01.770
Yeah, I know.

01:02:01.970 --> 01:02:03.330
(softly):
Yeah.

01:02:05.120 --> 01:02:07.200
She's getting so she's not used to me.

01:02:10.790 --> 01:02:11.900
I don't know.

01:02:12.090 --> 01:02:14.020
But she's-- so she's seven,

01:02:14.220 --> 01:02:16.900
and, um, and I-I started

01:02:17.090 --> 01:02:19.350
bringing her free Nikes every Sunday.

01:02:19.550 --> 01:02:22.810
And, you know, it's-it's the thing
that she looks forward to

01:02:23.010 --> 01:02:24.350
about seeing me, you know.

01:02:24.550 --> 01:02:26.690
So I-I bring her the shoes,
so she loves me.

01:02:26.890 --> 01:02:29.060
She got about 60 now.

01:02:29.260 --> 01:02:32.020
And so the sh-- the shoes, um,

01:02:32.220 --> 01:02:36.560
it makes me mean something to her.

01:02:36.760 --> 01:02:39.560
And if Phil shuts this division down,

01:02:39.760 --> 01:02:42.100
I'm ashamed to say
I-I'd still buy the shoes,

01:02:42.300 --> 01:02:46.000
even if it meant giving Phil money
and we make them in Taiwan.

01:02:47.290 --> 01:02:48.600
But I don't want to do that.

01:02:48.800 --> 01:02:52.980
I just want Avery to love me
and I want my job.

01:02:53.180 --> 01:02:56.980
And I think that you may have been
a little bit cavalier

01:02:57.180 --> 01:03:02.310
about the risks and, you know,
about taking us all with you.

01:03:02.510 --> 01:03:03.850
(sighs)

01:03:04.050 --> 01:03:07.770
I mean, if we're gonna make it,
w-we got to take risks.

01:03:07.970 --> 01:03:09.310
Spoken like a man

01:03:09.510 --> 01:03:11.950
without a seven-year-old
on Sunday afternoon.

01:03:18.580 --> 01:03:21.080
- I'm sorry.
- It's all right.

01:03:22.790 --> 01:03:25.730
I do see what you're doing with this.

01:03:25.930 --> 01:03:28.020
It's just a shoe, Rob.

01:03:28.220 --> 01:03:30.480
- It's...
- No.

01:03:30.680 --> 01:03:34.950
A shoe is always just a shoe
until someone steps into it.

01:03:38.250 --> 01:03:39.250
Hey.

01:03:45.160 --> 01:03:47.580
Happy birthday.

01:03:55.540 --> 01:03:56.700
Thank you.

01:03:58.790 --> 01:03:59.870
MOORE:
Hey, Sonny.

01:04:01.580 --> 01:04:04.100
(exhales slowly)

01:04:04.300 --> 01:04:05.520
We're ready.

01:04:05.720 --> 01:04:08.370
("Computer Love" by Zapp playing)

01:04:09.790 --> 01:04:11.620
(elevator bell dings)

01:04:13.290 --> 01:04:15.100
MOORE:
It's your birthday?

01:04:15.300 --> 01:04:16.270
Yeah. Yeah, yeah.

01:04:16.470 --> 01:04:18.850
And don't ask the next question.

01:04:19.050 --> 01:04:22.310
Well, here it is.

01:04:22.510 --> 01:04:26.440
This is the mock-up, but the shoe
will look basically like this.

01:04:26.640 --> 01:04:28.690
Wow.

01:04:28.890 --> 01:04:30.520
Yeah. Yeah.

01:04:30.720 --> 01:04:32.160
I got to say, it's beautiful.

01:04:34.160 --> 01:04:35.940
It has the logic of water.

01:04:36.140 --> 01:04:37.980
It's natural.

01:04:38.180 --> 01:04:40.580
Like the shoe was always here.

01:04:41.790 --> 01:04:43.440
Like it always existed.

01:04:43.640 --> 01:04:44.980
Right.

01:04:45.180 --> 01:04:48.830
Let's, uh, get the prototypes
processed right away.

01:04:50.790 --> 01:04:53.020
HORST:
So, on behalf of the whole family,

01:04:53.220 --> 01:04:55.230
we wish to welcome you in Germany

01:04:55.430 --> 01:04:57.690
and also thank you for making

01:04:57.890 --> 01:05:00.690
the excruciatingly long journey
to come and see us.

01:05:00.890 --> 01:05:02.060
KÄTHE:
Yes, thank you.

01:05:02.260 --> 01:05:05.650
HORST:
Michael, you're the next generation.

01:05:05.840 --> 01:05:09.350
You don't want to be grouped in
with Magic and Bird.

01:05:09.550 --> 01:05:11.310
You belong in our stable of athletes.

01:05:11.510 --> 01:05:12.770
FISHER:
You won't see this style anywhere.

01:05:12.970 --> 01:05:14.350
Those are all leather.

01:05:14.550 --> 01:05:16.520
DELORIS:
Are these the only options for the shoes?

01:05:16.720 --> 01:05:19.310
Well, the NBA has rules,
but we have options, yes.

01:05:19.510 --> 01:05:23.150
And I know this is a family business,
but who makes the final decision?

01:05:23.340 --> 01:05:26.310
FISHER: Well, unfortunately,
the family has suffered a tremendous loss.

01:05:26.510 --> 01:05:28.100
Käthe is calling the shots now.

01:05:28.300 --> 01:05:30.940
Yes. That's right.

01:05:31.140 --> 01:05:32.730
It is, uh, collaborative, though.

01:05:32.930 --> 01:05:35.690
(speaking German)

01:05:35.890 --> 01:05:37.560
A group decision.

01:05:37.760 --> 01:05:39.020
(conversing in German)

01:05:39.220 --> 01:05:41.040
That's what it is.

01:05:43.080 --> 01:05:45.940
("Sirius" by The Alan Parsons Project
playing)

01:05:46.140 --> 01:05:48.160
(engine roaring)

01:06:10.660 --> 01:06:12.940
(song fades)

01:06:13.140 --> 01:06:15.080
Oh, you like it up here?

01:06:17.540 --> 01:06:19.020
(sighs, grunts)

01:06:19.220 --> 01:06:21.730
This is the only comfortable couch
in the building, Phil.

01:06:21.930 --> 01:06:23.350
Where's Rob? Where's Howard?

01:06:23.550 --> 01:06:25.060
Uh, Rob's getting something to eat.

01:06:25.260 --> 01:06:27.830
It's not stealing
if the cashier isn't here.

01:06:29.830 --> 01:06:31.690
- You guys been here all weekend?
- Yeah.

01:06:31.890 --> 01:06:33.900
(chuckles) It, uh... it was nice.

01:06:34.090 --> 01:06:35.950
It was like the old Nike days.

01:06:38.410 --> 01:06:40.250
You got a name for it?

01:06:41.620 --> 01:06:42.650
For what?

01:06:42.840 --> 01:06:44.690
The Michael Jordan line.

01:06:44.890 --> 01:06:47.230
If we're making this offer
you're talking about,

01:06:47.430 --> 01:06:49.200
we damn well better have
a Michael Jordan line.

01:06:50.700 --> 01:06:54.690
Yeah.
Uh, well, there's a thought that, um...

01:06:54.890 --> 01:06:58.810
Pete actually thinks we should call it...

01:06:59.010 --> 01:07:00.330
Air Jordan.

01:07:02.500 --> 01:07:04.730
Hmm.

01:07:04.930 --> 01:07:06.900
- I don't know.
- Seriously?

01:07:07.090 --> 01:07:08.600
(stammers, sighs)

01:07:08.800 --> 01:07:09.980
Maybe it'll grow on me.

01:07:10.180 --> 01:07:11.730
Full budget?

01:07:11.930 --> 01:07:13.940
Yeah. Full budget.

01:07:14.140 --> 01:07:16.540
Well, how'd you come to that solution?

01:07:17.580 --> 01:07:19.290
I went for a run.

01:07:24.080 --> 01:07:26.330
Air Jordan. It's fucking fantastic.

01:07:30.370 --> 01:07:33.310
SONNY: <i>So I'll meet the Jordans out front.</i>
<i>I'll bring them up, and then,</i>

01:07:33.510 --> 01:07:36.230
Howard, you want me to pass them off
to you so you can talk about...

01:07:36.430 --> 01:07:39.190
Yeah, probably-probably best to let me
talk about my role down the road,

01:07:39.390 --> 01:07:41.480
and then I pass it off
to Rob with his thing.

01:07:41.680 --> 01:07:43.730
Great. Uh, and, Phil,
I want you to come in

